cellcount: an open-source and automated approach to cyanobacteria enumeration

Tyler E. Harman (Consolidated Safety Services, Fairfax, VA 22031, USA National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration, National Centers for Coastal Ocean Science, Beaufort, NC 28516, USA) , Mark W. Vandersea (National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration, National Centers for Coastal Ocean Science, Beaufort, NC 28516, USA) , David E. Berthold (Department of Biological Sciences, Florida International University, Miami, FL 33199, USA) , H. Dail Laughinghouse (Department of Biological Sciences, Florida International University, Miami, FL 33199, USA) , Brandon Boyd (U.S. Army Corps of Engineers, Engineer Research and Development Center, Vicksburg, MS 39180, USA) , Kaytee Pokrzywinski (National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration, National Centers for Coastal Ocean Science, Beaufort, NC 28516, USA)
2023-03-03

Summary

The cellcount package is a continuation of the report outlined in (Pokrzywinski, Boyd, and Smith 2019) and simplfies the quantification of bacteria and cyanobacteria via flourescence microscopy, using the computing language R. Functions within this package deconstruct images to assess individual cells, generate cell counts, and assess overall cell density from samples. In addition, additional tools are presented in this package using R Shiny (Chang et al. 2022) interfaces to demonstrate ease-of-use for researchers not familiar with the R environment. All materials outlined in this article, along with tutorials, are found in GitHub.

Statement of need

Harmful algal blooms (HABs) can exist within freshwater, estuarine, and marine environments. These can occur naturally within the environment and are stabilized in terms of population by means of nutrient availability, temperature, light, and competition with other phytoplankton (Catherine et al. 2013). However, in recent years, HABs have become increasingly common throughout the world, where climate change and anthropogenic impacts exacerbate the commonality of HABs. These blooms can cause harm to the aquatic environment, reducing phytoplankton assemblages, causing anoxic environments, and toxin production impacting higher trophic level organisms (Kurmayer, Christiansen, and Chorus 2003), (Stumpf et al. 2012), (Catherine et al. 2013), (Borges et al. 2019), and (Wood et al. 2020). From a public health aspect, the production of toxins can cause health issues or even death, but also cause impact from an economic standpoint such as reductions in property value and tourism in coastal areas (Carey et al. 2012).

Several methods have been established to understand HAB dynamics, primarily to develop monitoring protocols and establish mitigation practices. Microscopic enumeration has been considered as the gold standard for several decades as the method is widely available and simple to use (Jin et al. 2018). Although it is the standard method, microscopic enumeration can be time consuming, can be limited to small sample quantities, and requires significant knowledge of species identification (Li, Zhu, and Gao 2014) and (Jin et al. 2018). Technology has become significant in advancing scientific methods, and it is no less significant in its role in advancing enumeration processes. Several commercially available products such as the FlowCam (Fluid Imaging Technologies Inc.) and Imaging FlowCytobot (McLane Research Laboratories Inc.) can be used to simplify enumeration methods (REF). These technologies can be accurate, demonstrate time-savings, and simplify data collection (REF). However, several limitations can be observed such as particle size, misidentification of cells, and overall grouping of particles within samples, which can require assistance from researchers (REF). In addition, these technologies are expensive to purchase and maintain, reducing the nature of these technologies being widely available (Stauffer et al. 2019). A few studies have explored the process of automated cell enumeration methods by means of technology and software development, but promoting widespread availability. ImageJ is an open-source imaging analysis software and has available tools for particle/cell enumeration (Schulze et al. 2011). Other software algorithms have been developed to accomplish automated cellular enumeration (Jin et al. 2018). These methods can still be considered time-consuming (ImageJ) and require extensive knowledge of mathematical modeling (Jin et al. 2018).

The methods mentioned previously can be viable options for researchers regarding monitoring purposes, but can be expensive and require extensive training and materials. This leads to the suggestion of the need for accurate, low-cost, and widely available methods for rapid and simplistic automated enumeration of cells. A report released by (Pokrzywinski, Boyd, and Smith 2019) outlines an automated cyanobacteria enumeration script using the open-source programming language, R. (Pokrzywinski, Boyd, and Smith 2019) shows that while using fluorescent microscopy images, this enumeration script performs considerably well compared to standard microscopic enumeration methods. However, the previous presentation of this script can be considered extremely difficult to grasp for inexperienced R users and lacks organization. We utilized this script as a template for the development of an R package, involving the reduction of code into simple functions, expanding the ability for end-user modifications, development of a vignette for inexperienced users, and promoting open-source availability.

Overview of functions

The cellcount package is an open-source tool that can be accessed by researchers for use in the computing language R. Readers should note that the Bioconductor package EBImage (Pau et al. 2010), tiff (Urbanek and Johnson 2022), raster (Hijmans et al. 2023), and pixmap (Bivand, Leisch, and Maechler 2021) packages are needed for use of this toolset for accurate data collection.

The cellcount package can be installed locally and used within the RStudio environment. The cellcount functions are to be used in sequential order, as outlined in the sandbox_analysis_test.R script embedded within the cellcount package. Once image files have been identified, users can begin to upload their images using tiff package functions (see readTIFF). From here, images within the R environment must be converted into formats that R can use to process images. The greyscale function converts 24-bit images (RGB) into 8-bit images, and contains a built-in numerical contrast adjustment.

greyscale <- function(x, contrast = 2) {
  x <- contrast * x
  x <- x[, , 1] + x[, , 2] + x[, , 3]
  x <- x / max(x)
  x <- normalize(x, inputRange = c(0.1, 0.75))
  return(x)
}

Figure 1: Converted greyscale image of Microcystis sp.

The mapped function is used to turn 8-bit images into a data matrix from the dimensions of the initial image, using the “as.matrix” function (see the data.table package), and includes a pixel intensity threshold adjustment. This removes any pixel that is under the threshold value to easily separate the background from cells.

mapped <- function(x, threshold = 0.3) {
  x <- as.matrix(x)
  x[x < threshold] <- 0
  return(x)
}

The border function is built into several other functions within cellcount (i.e. countImages, image_convert, etc.), where its primarily goal is to predict cells along a predetermined border and to remove these cells from the final cell count estimate from each image. (WHY IS THAT IMPORTANT-OUTLINE IT HERE).

border <- function(x, y) {
  c(x[1:y[1], 1], x[1:y[1], y[2]], x[1, 1:y[2]], x[y[1], 1:y[2]])
}

The image_convert functions take the data matrices corresponding to each image and counts individual cells within an image, omitting the cells indentified from the border function. Fluorescence microscopy images analyzed by this function are of a single fluorescent dimension (i.e. auto-fluorescence, DAPI, etc.). End-users should note that this function is useful only for analyzing images containing single-cell cyanobacteria. fillHull is placed first in this function before watershed in order to disseminate single-cells with more accuracy. A parallel function in cellcount, image_convert2, is similarly organized but meant for filamentous or colonial-type cyanobacteria. The difference with this is largely where watershed is placed before fillHull, opposite of image_convert, which improves accuracy. Within these two functions, several variables can be adjusted by end-users, such as the width and height of the rectangular window (see EBImage), the pixel area threshold (i.e., removes cells or other objects under a certain pixel area), and the tolerance and ‘ext’ variables (see EBImage).

image_convert <- function(x, w = 17, h = 17, offset = 0.001, areathresh = 50, tolerance= 0.5, ext = 1) {
  image <- thresh(x, w = w, h = h, offset = offset)
  image1 <- fillHull(image)
  image2 <- watershed(distmap(image1), tolerance = tolerance, ext = ext)
  nf <- computeFeatures.shape(image2)
  nr <- which(nf[, "s.area"] < areathresh)
  image3 <- rmObjects(image2, nr)
  return(image3)
}
image_convert2 <- function(x, w = 17, h = 17, offset = 0.001, areathresh = 50, tolerance= 0.5, ext = 1) {
  image <- thresh(x, w = w, h = h, offset = offset)
  image1 <- watershed(distmap(image), tolerance = tolerance, ext = ext)
  image2 <- fillHull(image1)
  nf <- computeFeatures.shape(image2)
  nr <- which(nf[, "s.area"] < areathresh)
  image3 <- rmObjects(image2, nr)
  return(image3)
}

Once the conversion occurs, the countImages function generates a color-label image, where each separated cell is given a unique color-label. This function includes removing cells along a predetermined border using the border function in order to improve count accuracy. End-users may view these color-label images using the display function (see the arm package).

countImages <- function(image, normalize = TRUE, removeEdgeCells = TRUE) {
  if (removeEdgeCells) {
    dims <- dim(image)
    border1 <- border(image, dims)
    ids <- unique(border1[which(border1 != 0)])
    inner <- rmObjects(image, ids)
    EBImage::colorLabels(inner, normalize = normalize)
  } else {
    EBImage::colorLabels(image, normalize = normalize)
  }
}

Figure 2: A converted color-label image of Microcystis sp.

The final function, countCells, counts the number of cells resulting from the image generated by the countImages function. Once again, the border function is integrated here to omit counting cells within its predetermined border. Other items within the sandbox_analysis_test.R script enables users to analyze images in bulk, generate tables of results, calculate cell densities using equations from (Wetzel and Likens 2000), and export data to .csv files for easy organization.

countCells <- function(x) {
  countAll <- max(x)
  dims <- dim(x)
  border1 <- border(x, dims)
  ids <- unique(border1[which(border1 != 0)])
  countInner <- countAll - length(ids)
  return(countInner)
}

Graphical user interface using Shiny apps

Informal discussions with researchers ignited the development of a graphical user interface (GUI) using Shiny apps, paired with functions from the cellcount package. This results in the use of two functions, input_data and analyze images, to run the entire analysis process as outlined in the sandbox_analysis_test.R script. In addition to packages required by cellcount, these GUIs require the shiny (Chang et al. 2022), shinyalert (Attali, Edwards, and Wang 2021), shinyFiles (Pedersen et al. 2022), shinyjs (Attali 2021), and beepr (Baath and Dobbyn 2018) libraries.

input_data uses a Shiny app UI for end-users to easily fill out the needed information in order to correctly label analyzed images, provide numerical inputs for variables, select image analysis type, and easily select directories containing images and saving data. The UI format is a simple approach, with tabs outlined on the left-hand side of the interface for its respective purpose (i.e., directory selection, analysis type selection, etc.). Each tab contains interactive buttons or drop-down menus for users to enter in the respective information or make appropriate selections for their analysis needs. Shiny directory buttons provide users a simple and familiar interface to select appropriate folders containing images or to set up save directories. Alert modals (see shinyalert) are used for users to interact and provide information in text format, with helpful dialog to keep users organized and informed of the information needed. Once all information is provided, users select the “Completion” tab and click the “submit data entries” button to complete the data input process.

analyze_images uses a simplistic Shiny UI which consists of two buttons, one to run the analysis and the other to close the UI interface. Once the proper data has been entered from the input_data function, users simply click the “Run Image Analysis” button to begin. Sounds from the beepr package alert users of completion of the analysis, where the “Close window” button exits the UI window. Users can navigate to their specific directories to find analyzed images and related .csv files for their review.

Limitiations and warnings

The current version of this package may be limited for some users regarding processing power. Analysis with this package uses local memory, which may be limiting if expected to analyze large amounts of images in batches. We recommend at least 16GB of localized RAM, the use of a cloud computing supercomputer, or organize images in easier-to-analyze batches to reduce local memory strain.

Users must be aware that this package does not contain abilities to identify distinct cells. The development of this package utilized carefully cultured monoculture of various cyanobacteria species. Users may find difficulty in using this analysis tool if cultures contain heavy amounts of particulates, other cellular debris, and contamination of other species. It is advised to use this tool for single-species only. Future developments of this tool include identifying features and building image libraries of specific cellular species for use in environmental samples.

Outside of package limitations, users must be aware of limitations that may arise from poor microscopy imaging; reduce lighting as much as possible, avoid heavy background fluorescence, and so forth. Good images produce good results - keep this in mind as you utilize this tool.

Conclusions

cellcount provides an open-source approach to cyanobacteria enumeration that is accurate and rapid compared to standardized microscopy methods. The open-source approach allows researchers to access this tool for free and to modify and make additions the existing code to fulfill their particular needs, whereas the Shiny GUI allows users of all coding backgrounds to utilize this analysis tool.
